{"questionId":"3131607","questionHtml":"<p>The owner of the rough ground converts the southern quarter into a field over which Huw can run at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo> </mo><mi>km</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>. The following diagram shows the optimal route,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HJKS</mi></math>, in this new situation. You are given that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>HJ</mi><mo>]</mo></math>&nbsp;is parallel to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>KS</mi><mo>]</mo></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/9507fc1c6b4ec787206f581e3d58fc480159d501.png\"></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Using a similar result to that given in part (c)(iii), at the point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>, determine <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MJ</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/b313e086201ebb6ef6733aad1ddb95c63342cab7.png\"></p>\n<p>let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MJ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>y</mi><mo> </mo><mi>km</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></math> be the points on the new boundary directly below <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>\n<p>attempt to find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZK</mi></math> in terms of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MJ</mi></math> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>KW</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>y</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZK</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>y</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>km</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to use the result from (c)(iii) at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>y</mi><msqrt><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mfrac><mo>÷</mo><mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>y</mi></mrow></mfenced><msqrt><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>y</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Accept <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> in place of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mtext>leading&nbsp;to</mtext><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mi>y</mi><msqrt><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>16</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>÷</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>y</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msqrt><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>y</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn></msqrt></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>valid method for solving this equation, eg drawing graphs of both sides of the equation, using SOLVER, etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>solution is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>53</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>combining the field into one region with height <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi>km</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><msqrt><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><msqrt><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Both expressions, or their ratio, are required for the <em><strong>A1</strong></em> to be awarded.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>therefore</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi><msqrt><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><msqrt><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>valid method for solving&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempting to find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MJ</mi></math> in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> e.g. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MJ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MJ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>53</mn></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[6 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"3131607","referenceCode":"23M.3.AHL.TZ2.1d","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"The owner of the rough ground converts the southern quarter into a field over which Huw can run at 15 km h-1. The following diagram shows the optimal route, HJKS, in this new situa","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 6]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.7—Optimisation","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.6—Modelling skills"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}